{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17412771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17412771"},"attributes":{"position":5,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"290"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487242"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:02:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:02:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"290"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261074"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:40:20+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":19,"questionsAnswered":7,"marksTotal":19,"marksAttainable":7,"marksAttempted":7,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:39:59+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.14,"questionsCorrect":1,"marksCorrect":1},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/290"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.09,0.27,0.16,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"290"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83500"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/290"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"290"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68373"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"185"},{"type":"tags","id":"1887"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42047"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43790"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83500"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 85-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a 12-month history of increasing fatigue. His wife reports that he has looked very \u0022off colour\u0022 and is concerned that he has become more irritable at times. He has unintentionally lost eight kilograms in weight. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, a partial gastrectomy, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His medications include metformin and a fluticasone/salmeterol inhaler. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his gait is unsteady and wide-based. Neurologic examination shows mild symmetrical weakness with loss of proprioception and vibration sense. Romberg sign is present.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple sclerosis","Diabetic peripheral neuropathy","Thiamine deficiency","Spinal cord mass lesion","Subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of\u003Cstrong\u003E subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord\u003C/strong\u003E, likely secondary to vitamin B12 deficiency.\u00a0Symmetrical weakness, loss of proprioception and vibration sensation and wide-based ataxia are consistent with loss of the dorsal/posterior and lateral columns of the spinal cord. Vitamin B12 (cobalamin) is needed for the development and myelination of these columns and a deficiency can lead to subacute combined degeneration. The deficiency is likely secondary to the partial gastrectomy, as a consequence of reduced parietal cells and thus decreased intrinsic factor synthesis, which Vitamin B12 uptake is dependent on. Vitamin B12 deficiency also causes macrocytic anaemia, which results in pallor and fatigue.\u00a0Vitamin B12 deficiency may also manifest with malabsorption, ocular symptoms, cognitive deficits, neuropsychiatric features (megaloblastic madness \u2013 depression, mania, delusions, irritability), personality changes and infertility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECauses of B12 deficiency include dietary deficiency or malabsorption e.g. (in pernicious anaemia, gastrectomy, coeliac disease, gastric atrophy, autoimmune conditions, or medication-related).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E should be suspected when there is focal or multifocal insult to the central nervous system interspersed through time. Its typical demographic is young women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA positive Romberg sign suggests ataxia. The wide based gait suggests cerebellar ataxia instead of sensory (proprioceptive) ataxia, which would be inconsistent with\u003Cstrong\u003E diabetic peripheral neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E. We would expect a high stepping gait or a vestibular gait if it is sensory ataxia, which may occur in diabetic peripheral neuropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Espinal cord mass lesion\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially present with these deficits (and the fatigue and neuropsychiatric features potentially explainable by advanced age and incipient cognitive impairment), however the time-scale and specific pattern of impairments made subacute combined degeneration more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThiamine (vitamin B1) deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E manifests clinically as beriberi or Wernicke-Korsakoff syndrome (or Wernicke encephalopathy, WE). Adult beriberi can develop as a symmetrical peripheral neuropathy characterised by both sensory and motor impairments (dry beriberi), or as cardiac involvement in addition to neuropathy (beriberi). It should not cause irritability. WE presents acutely, characterised by nystagmus, ophthalmoplegia, ataxia, and confusion, which the patient does not have.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Causes of B12 deficiency include dietary deficiency or malabsorption e.g. (in pernicious anaemia, gastrectomy, coeliac disease, gastric atrophy, autoimmune conditions, or medication-related).","The dorsal column / medial leminiscus system relays touch, vibration, pressure and two-point discrimination sensations."],"references":["Green R, Allen LH, Bj\u00f8rke-Monsen AL, Brito A, Gu\u00e9ant JL, Miller JW, et al. Vitamin B12 deficiency. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2017;3:17040. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28660890/","Stabler SP. Vitamin B12 deficiency. The N Eng J Med. 2013;368:149\u201360. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/nejmcp1113996","Saji AM, Lui F, De Jesus O. Spinal Cord Subacute Combined Degeneration. [Updated 2024 Apr 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560728/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68373"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"290"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68373"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-04T20:29:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-04T20:37:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"290"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83500"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"t